    {
      "id": "ch5_5_3_008",
      "lesson": "5.3",
      "type": "basic",
      "front": "What are the four numeral systems supported by C++ literals?",
      "back": "<ul><li>Decimal (base 10) - no prefix</li><li>Binary (base 2) - 0b prefix</li><li>Hexadecimal (base 16) - 0x prefix</li><li>Octal (base 8) - 0 prefix</li></ul>",
      "tags": [
        "cpp",
        "literals",
        "numeral-systems"
      ],
      "source": "5.3 - Numeral systems",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "id": "ch5_5_3_009",
      "lesson": "5.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "concept": "When to use different numeral systems",
      "explanation": "Different numeral systems are useful for different purposes:<ul><li>Binary: bit flags, bit manipulation</li><li>Hex: memory addresses, colors, bit patterns</li><li>Octal: file permissions (Unix/Linux), rarely used otherwise</li><li>Decimal: most common use cases</li></ul>",
      "examples": [
        "0b1010'1100  // Binary for bit flags",
        "0xFF00FF    // Hex for RGB color (magenta)",
        "0755        // Octal for file permissions"
      ],
